d feminist theory. Despite the prominence of "state of nature" ideas in modern political theory, Hirschmann argues, theories of freedom actually advance a social constructivist understanding of humanity. By rereading "human nature" in light of this insight, Hirschmann uncovers theories of freedom that are both more historically accurate and more relevant to contemporary politics. Pigeonholing canonical theorists as proponents of either "positive" or "negative" liberty is historically inaccurate, she demonstrates, because theorists deploy both conceptions of freedom simultaneously throughout their work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConstructivism (Philosophy). 0aLibertyvPhilosophy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 0aPHILOSOPHYvPolitical. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvFeminism &xFeminist Theory. 0aSex rolevPolitical aspects. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspects. 0aSocial classesvPolitical aspects. 0aWomen's rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aHobbes, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKant, Immanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLocke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMill, John Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Jean-Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082416840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400824168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400824168.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  